        <section id="faq-506">
            <img alt="" decoding="async" src="/assets/svgs/fern.svg" height="483" width="224" aria-hidden="true" class="cs-fern">
            <div class="cs-container">
                <div class="cs-content">
                    <span class="cs-topper">
                        <span class="cs-topper-dot" aria-hidden="true"></span>
                        <img alt="" decoding="async" src="/assets/svgs/arrow-right.svg" height="10" width="48" aria-hidden="true" class="cs-topper-arrow">
                         FAQ
                    </span>
                    <h2 class="cs-title">Landscaping Questions for Las Cruces Homeowners</h2>
                </div>
                <ul class="cs-faq-list">
                    <li class="cs-faq-item">
                        <details class="cs-faq">
                            <summary class="cs-faq-summary">
                                <span class="cs-faq-question">How much does landscaping cost in Las Cruces?</span>
                                <span class="cs-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">
                                    <svg height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="24">
                                        <path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2"/>
                                    </svg>
                                </span>
                            </summary>
                            <div class="cs-faq-body">
                                <p>Most residential yard landscaping projects in Las Cruces range from $3,000 to $15,000 depending on yard size, plant selection, and scope of work. A small front-yard refresh might run $2,500 to $5,000, while a full backyard installation with turf, trees, and beds can reach $10,000 or more. We provide free on-site estimates so you get an exact price before any work begins.</p>
                            </div>
                        </details>
                    </li>
                    <li class="cs-faq-item">
                        <details class="cs-faq">
                            <summary class="cs-faq-summary">
                                <span class="cs-faq-question">What plants grow best in Las Cruces?</span>
                                <span class="cs-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">
                                    <svg height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="24">
                                        <path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2"/>
                                    </svg>
                                </span>
                            </summary>
                            <div class="cs-faq-body">
                                <p>Plants that thrive here are adapted to alkaline soils (pH 7.5–8.5), intense sun, and limited rainfall. We regularly install desert willow, red yucca, lantana, Texas sage, Mexican honeysuckle, and salvia. For shade trees, we recommend Chilean mesquite, live oak, and Arizona ash. These species handle the heat without heavy watering once established.</p>
                            </div>
                        </details>
                    </li>
                    <li class="cs-faq-item">
                        <details class="cs-faq">
                            <summary class="cs-faq-summary">
                                <span class="cs-faq-question">When is the best time to plant in Las Cruces?</span>
                                <span class="cs-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">
                                    <svg height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="24">
                                        <path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2"/>
                                    </svg>
                                </span>
                            </summary>
                            <div class="cs-faq-body">
                                <p>Fall (September through November) and early spring (February through April) are the best planting windows in southern New Mexico. Cooler temperatures give roots 8–12 weeks to establish before summer heat arrives. We schedule every project around these windows so your plants get the strongest possible start.</p>
                            </div>
                        </details>
                    </li>
                    <li class="cs-faq-item">
                        <details class="cs-faq">
                            <summary class="cs-faq-summary">
                                <span class="cs-faq-question">Can you install a green lawn in the desert?</span>
                                <span class="cs-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">
                                    <svg height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="24">
                                        <path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2"/>
                                    </svg>
                                </span>
                            </summary>
                            <div class="cs-faq-body">
                                <p>Yes. We install warm-season sod varieties like Bermuda and buffalo grass that handle Las Cruces’s summer heat. The key is proper soil prep, correct grading, and an irrigation system matched to the turf type. We also offer hybrid designs that combine turf areas with desert landscaping to keep water bills lower.</p>
                            </div>
                        </details>
                    </li>
                    <li class="cs-faq-item">
                        <details class="cs-faq">
                            <summary class="cs-faq-summary">
                                <span class="cs-faq-question">How long does a landscaping project take?</span>
                                <span class="cs-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">
                                    <svg height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="24">
                                        <path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2"/>
                                    </svg>
                                </span>
                            </summary>
                            <div class="cs-faq-body">
                                <p>Most residential landscaping projects take 3 to 7 days from start to finish. A focused front-yard install can wrap up in 2 to 3 days, while a full-property project with grading, turf, trees, and beds may take 1 to 2 weeks. We give you a clear timeline at the estimate stage so there are no surprises.</p>
                            </div>
                        </details>
                    </li>
                    <li class="cs-faq-item">
                        <details class="cs-faq">
                            <summary class="cs-faq-summary">
                                <span class="cs-faq-question">Do you offer a guarantee on your landscaping work?</span>
                                <span class="cs-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">
                                    <svg height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="24">
                                        <path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2"/>
                                    </svg>
                                </span>
                            </summary>
                            <div class="cs-faq-body">
                                <p>Yes. Every landscaping project from Brainard's Greenscapes comes with our workmanship guarantee. If anything we installed fails due to our work, we fix it at no cost. Plants are covered by a separate plant guarantee: if a plant doesn’t survive during the guarantee period under normal care, we replace it free of charge.</p>
                            </div>
                        </details>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </section>
